  ('source-12', '16', 'Weick', 'Sensemaking', '1995', '', '', '', 'Weick, K. E. (1995). <em>Sensemaking in organizations</em>. Sage Publications.', 'Karl Weick’s work in sensemaking, though emerging as a corrective to overly rigid managerial logic, sits firmly within a human-centered frame. Weick views sensemaking from an action-oriented lens: situations become words, and words become actions. Organizational worlds are brought into existence through categories, labels, and symbolic interpretation—a process that is inherently reductionist. Embodied knowledge, tacit knowledge, and more-than-human signals fall outside this frame. Importantly, Weick highlights that power shapes who gets to define the categories that constitute organizational reality: those with greater access and authority shape how others make sense of their environment, act, and participate. Mainstream management and organizational theory has historically privileged abstract, representational knowledge—metrics, categories, models, indicators, and quantitative data—and Weick’s framework both reflects and reinforces this narrowing tendency. His approach explains how meaning-making influences organizational action, but rarely asks to what end, or who and what are excluded from participation. This source is valuable to my literature review because it illustrates how dominant organizational epistemologies are structured to exclude non-human and non-cognitive forms of knowing. In asking how different organizational worldviews shape leadership values and culture, Weick’s sensemaking framework exemplifies how Western management thought encodes what is legible, who counts as an actor, and what kinds of knowledge are deemed actionable. It provides a critical foil against which relational, posthumanist, and Indigenous frameworks can be assessed.', 16),
  ('source-13', '17', 'Weick & Obstfeld', 'Sensemaking', '2005', '', '', '', 'Weick, K. E., Sutcliffe, K. M., & Obstfeld, D. (2005). Organizing and the process of sensemaking. <em>Organization Science, 16</em>(4), 409–421. https://doi.org/10.1287/orsc.1050.0133', 'Weick, Sutcliffe, and Obstfeld extend sensemaking theory by examining how organizational actors continuously make sense of ambiguous, unfolding situations through retrospective interpretation and coordinated action. This work deepens the argument that organizational worlds are constituted through categories, labels, and symbolic interpretation—a framing that is inherently reductionist. Embodied knowledge, tacit knowledge, and more-than-human signals fall outside this frame. The emphasis on cognitive and linguistic meaning-making reinforces the primacy of human interpretation, even as it acknowledges that meaning is socially negotiated and context-dependent. Mainstream management and organizational theory has historically privileged abstract, representational knowledge—metrics, categories, models, and quantitative data—and this framework narrows what organizations can perceive and the relationships that may emerge with/in ecosystems. Many ecological relationships remain invisible because they resist measurement and visualization or dominant modes of communication. This source serves my literature review by demonstrating how influential sensemaking theories, despite their sophistication, remain tethered to human-centered epistemologies. In the context of my research question—how organizational worldviews shape leadership values, culture, and decision-making—this work helps explain why mechanistic and representational forms of knowledge production remain dominant. Placing this work in dialogue with relational and posthumanist traditions surfaces the onto-epistemological limits of dominant organizational thought.', 17),
  ('source-14', '18', 'Maitlis & Christianson', 'Sensemaking', '2014', '', '', '', 'Maitlis, S., & Christianson, M. (2014). Sensemaking in organizations: Taking stock and moving forward. <em>The Academy of Management Annals, 8</em>(1), 57–125. https://doi.org/10.1080/19416520.2014.873177', '', 18),
