  ('source-52', '27', 'Latour', 'Practice Theory', '2005', '', '', '', 'Latour, B. (2005). <em>Reassembling the social: An introduction to Actor-Network Theory</em>. Oxford University Press.', 'Philosopher Bruno Latour writes that “to limit the discussion to humans, their interests, their subjectivities, and their rights, will appear as strange a few years from now as having denied the right to vote to slaves, poor people or women.” Latour’s provocation does more than call for the ethical inclusion of nonhuman actors; it exposes a deeper ontological failure in how organizational life has been imagined. Latour reveals the limits of frameworks that assume only humans are the ones who get to matter, act, or decide. Through Actor-Network Theory, Latour argues that agency is distributed across configurations of humans, nonhumans, materials, infrastructures, and environments—a proposition that fundamentally destabilizes the human-centered ontology of mainstream management thought. Social life, for Latour, is not a fixed context within which organizations operate, but an ongoing achievement continually assembled and reassembled through heterogeneous networks of actors. This source is foundational to my literature review because it offers one of the most rigorous philosophical challenges to anthropocentric organizational theory. In examining how different organizational worldviews shape leadership values, decision-making, and structure, Latour’s framework insists that any adequate account of organizational life must include the full range of actants—human and nonhuman—whose relations constitute organizational reality. This has direct implications for how leadership, agency, and accountability are understood, making Actor-Network Theory an essential conceptual resource for the relational, ecological organizational theory this research aims to advance.', 27),
  ('source-22', '28', 'de Vaujany & Silva', 'Posthumanism', '2024', '', '', '', 'de Vaujany, F.-X., Gherardi, S., & Silva, P. (Eds.). (2024). <em>Organization studies and posthumanism: Towards a more-than-human world</em>. Routledge. https://doi.org/10.4324/9781032617169', '', 28),
