  ('source-50', '60', 'Wahl', 'Grey Literature', '2016', '', '', '', 'Wahl, D. C. (2016). <em>Designing regenerative cultures</em>. Triarchy Press.', 'Wahl argues for a regenerative culture grounded in local, place-based practices and an emphasis on long-term ecological resilience rather than short-term economic gain. Sustainability, in his view, is insufficient if it merely slows degradation; organizations must actively participate in restoring the conditions that allow life to flourish through respect and reciprocity. Wahl frames the role of organizations as ecologically embedded and place-sourced, calling for a fundamental reorientation of design, leadership, and culture toward the health of living systems. He draws on systems thinking, biomimicry, and Indigenous ecological knowledge to argue that regenerative cultures are not a future aspiration but an ecological necessity—rooted in practices that attune organizations to the rhythms, cycles, and relationships of the ecosystems they inhabit. This source is important to my literature review because it translates the onto-epistemological shift toward ecological embeddedness into concrete organizational and cultural terms. In examining how different organizational worldviews shape leadership values and structure, Wahl provides a practitioner-facing account of what it might look like for organizations to genuinely reorient their culture, decision-making, and design around ecological health and regenerative relationships. This makes it a valuable bridge between the philosophical and critical sources in my bibliography and the practical question of how organizational culture can be transformed in ways that sustain life rather than deplete it.', 60);